label: Type Capable Fn
TypeCapableFn
items.comment: TypeCapableFn takes an instance-level CapabilityPredicate, and returns a type-level version of that predicate. In other words, if CAP-PRED is an instance-level CapabilityPredicate, then (TypeCapableFn CAP-PRED) is the corresponding type-level predicate. A member of CapabilityPredicate_InstanceLevel is a predicate which can be used to assert that an individual thing has the capability of playing a certain role in a type of event. So, '(CAP-PRED INDIVIDUAL EVENT-TYPE ROLE)' means that INDIVIDUAL has the capability CAP-PRED of playing ROLE in EVENT-TYPE. The corresponding type-level CapabilityPredicate, '(TypeCapableFn CAP-PRED)', allows one to say that a type of individual has the capability of playing a certain role in a type of event. So, '((TypeCapableFn CAP-PRED) TYPE EVENT-TYPE ROLE)' means that TYPE has the capability CAP-PRED of playing ROLE in EVENT-TYPE. To say that a type of thing has a capability means that a typical, or normal, individual of that type has the instance-level capability.

TerrestrialFrameOfReferenceMt
Mx4rvViA5ZwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Terrestrial Frame Of Reference Vocabulary knowledge
items.comment: This microtheory assumes that directions are meant in relation to the earth. I.e. `up` follows a line normal to the earth's surface. Horizontal is parallel to earth's surface. North is in the direction the compass points. This microtheory also assumes that the earth and the ground is stationary (except during earthquakes). It also assumes that tangible objects feel the downward force of gravity. Every tangible object in this context has a value for altitudeAboveSeaLevel. It also assumes that the distances between all objects is less than half the circumference of the earth, otherwise stating that eastOf was a TransitiveBinaryPredicate would result in inaccurate conclusions e.g. that El Paso was east of Austin. This microtheory allows for objects to be at arbitrarily high altitudes. See NearEarthsSurfaceMt for a microtheory which makes stronger assumptions. A map context would be different than TerrestrialFrameOfReferenceMt because 'north' on a map is often the same as 'up'. 'North' on a map, although it depicts 'terrestrial north', only happens to be parallel to 'terrestrial north' when the map is appropriately aligned.

label: today
Today-Indexical
items.comment: Today_Indexical is a special CalendarDay which denotes the current date from the perspective of the instantiation of CycTheCollection that is currently being run (see Cyc). If one asks (indexicalReferent Today_Indexical ?X) one will get an answer in which ?X is bound to whatever the date is according to the central processing unit of Cyc. Thus the referent of Today_Indexical does not vary with the Microtheory in which one asks (indexicalReferent Today_Indexical ?X). Instead the referent of Today_Indexical varies from day to day. In contrast see also Now_Generally which is not necessarily a CalendarDay and does not necessarily change referent as real time marches forward. See Now which is a TimePoint analog of Today_Indexical. However, unlike Now, Today_Indexical does not necessarily temporally subsume Now_Generally in RealTimeMt.

label: the sky
TheSkyAboveHere
items.comment: TheSkyAboveHere is what one sees when one looks up while outside, not under any trees, shelters, umbrellas etc.. This concept does not make much sense when Here is not on or near the groundOf PlanetEarth. When the time of the viewing location is DaytimeHours, TheSkyAboveHere is blue and the sun is in it (unless there's a total eclispe, or it is near sunset, sunrise etc..). When it is nighttime, the TheSkyAboveHere is black and there are stars in it. Note that if the weather of Here are CloudyArea, or if Here is Indoors_IsolatedFromOutside the TheSkyAboveHere can not be seen. TheSkyAboveHere is similar to the notion of 'the heavens'. Often TheSkyAboveHere is what one refers to when one says 'the sky'. However, see also SkyFn, TheWholeSky, and PieceOfSky.

label: Sub Sentence Fn
SubSentenceFn
items.comment: An expression of the form (SubSentenceFn SENTENCE SUB) is used to pick out an instance of CycLAtomicSentence. Specifically, it is used to denote the CycLAtomicSentence SUB with regard to its being a syntactic element of the canonical representation of the CycLSentence represented by the (CycLObjectTypeFn CycLSentence) SENTENCE. Although closely related to the syncategorematic 'function' Quote, the expression (SubSentenceFn SENTENCE SUB) does not denote SUB per se. Instead, it serves to pick out SUB as a part of the canonical representation of the CycLSentence SENTENCE. The primary utility of this function is for representing assertions about CycL sentences in a form that can be easily fed out to alternative representational systems that cannot support second-order representations. The contextualization of SUB relative to SENTENCE allows us to unambiguously refer to the elements of one CycLSentence, even if syntactically-identical elements appear in multiple CycLSentences. NOTE: The first argument of this function is not quoted so that it is possible to use a term to refer to the relevant CycLSentence without the actual symbols of SUB appearing within SENT.

items.comment: A generalization of UnsuccessfulAttemptToFn. '(UnsatisfactoryAttemptToFn ACT-TYPE)' denotes the specialization of Attempting in which each instance was an attempt to do an instance of ACT-TYPE but, for some reason or other, the performance of the action was not as the performed wanted it to be. For instance, if I am trying to kill A, but I instead kill B, then that action is an instance of (UnsatisfactoryAttemptToFn KillingByOrganism). Although it was in fact a killing, the thing killed was not the intended target. Note that, in the case I describe, that action is not an instance of (UnsuccessfulAttemptToFn KillingByOrganism) -- the act was successful in the sense that I did manage to kill someone. But, the act was not satisfactory to me because I did not kill the intended target. If the reason an act was "unsatisfactory" was because it was unsuccessful in the UnsuccessfulAttemptToFn sense, then the action is not an instance of ACT-TYPE.

UnsatisfactoryAttemptToFn

A binary SetDenotingFunction and ScopingRelation that takes a variable and an open sentence to a set, where the open sentence specifies a necessary and sufficient membership condition for the set. If SENT is an open CycLSentence_Assertible in which VAR is the only variable occuring free, (TheSetOf VAR SENT) is the Set_Mathematical of exactly those things that satisfy SENT. For example, (TheSetOf ?X (and (isa ?X Dog) (mainColorOfObject ?X BlackColor))) is the set of black dogs.

Note that if VAR does not occur free in SENT, or is not the only variable occuring free in SENT, the term (TheSetOf VAR SENT) will be itself be open (see CycLOpenNonAtomicTerm) and thus will not denote anything. Given that a true sentence is satisfied by everything, we stipulate that (TheSetOf VAR SENT) is undefined whenever SENT is closed in order to avoid commitment to a "universal set".

See also TheSet, which is used to specify a set by enumerating its elements. And see TheCollectionOf.

items.comment:
An instance of ZeroDimensionalUnitOfMeasure (q.v.) that takes one or two numbers or other NumericIntervals (q.v.) as argument(s) and returns the continuous numeric-interval that spans between and includes those arguments. Given one argument, Unity behaves like an identity function.

More precisely: for any numeric-interval NUM, (Unity NUM) = NUM; and for any two numeric-intervals LO and HI such that (greaterThanOrEqualTo HI LO), (Unity LO HI) is the numeric-interval that ranges from the least point-value (see Number_General) subsumed by (see quantitySubsumes) LO to the greatest point-value subsumed by HI.

In practice, LO and HI will typically be two distinct RealNumbers, and (Unity LO HI) will be the continuous ProperIntervalOnNumberLine that ranges from LO to HI. For example, (Unity 1 10) is the interval from 1 to 10 inclusive. But note that LO and/or HI might themselves be proper intervals: (Unity (Unity 7 9) 11) is thus the interval from 7 to 11 inclusive.

Unity is classified as a UnitOfMeasure mainly in order to simplify the application of quasi-mathematical operations (e.g. PerFn, UnitProductFn) to units-of-measure generally. For example, TimesPerDay is defined as the result of "dividing" (via PerFn) Unity by DaysDuration.

(portNumberForSKS TripleStoreKS-Generic 80)

(codeMapping

the square root of ______
SquareRootFn
items.comment:
A unary MathematicalFunctionOnScalars that is the arithmetical operation that takes a (non-negative) number to its non-negative square root, extended to measurable ScalarIntervals generally. (SquareRootFn SCALAR) is by definition equal to ROOT: the NonNegativeScalarInterval such that (TimesFn ROOT ROOT) is equal to SCALAR.

For example, (SquareRootFn 81) is equal to 9 and (SquareRootFn (SquareMile 9)) is equal to (Mile 3).

Note that while this holds: 

  (inverseQuantFunctions_Nonsymmetric SquaredFn SquareRootFn) ,

this does not: 

  (inverseQuantFunctions_Nonsymmetric SquareRootFn SquaredFn) .

For the square of the non-negative square root of X is always X, but the non-negative square root of the square of X is not always X (e.g. where X is -2). Thus, SquareRootFn and SquaredFn might be considered "quasi-inverses".

A binary function that takes as arguments a CycLFormula and an integer-list that specifies a position within it, and returns the CycLTerm (if any) that appears in that position in that formula. The term might be an immediate constituent of the formula, or it might be nested (to any depth) inside some other constituent(s).

(TermWithPositionInFormulaFn INTEGER-LIST FORMULA) is the term TERM (if there is one) that occurs in the location in FORMULA that is precisely described by INTEGER-LIST, according to the following convention. The first integer in INTEGER-LIST is the number of an argument-place in FORMULA that is occupied by either (a) TERM itself or (b) by some sub-formula SUBFORMULA that contains TERM. In case (a), TERM's exact location has been identified, and INTEGER-LIST will contain no furtherintegers. In case (b), the second integer in INTEGER-LIST is the number of the argument-place in SUBFORMULA that is occupied by either (a) TERM itself or (b) by some sub-formula SUBSUBFORMULA that contains TERM. And so on.

For example, (TermWithPositionInFormulaFn (TheList 2 1) (isa Muffet (AdultFn Dog))) is the CycL term 'Dog' (as opposed to the collection of dogs).

This function corresponds to the predicate termHasPositionInFormula.

StringPostremoveFn is an evaluatable function that takes two strings as its arguments. (StringPostremoveFn STRING1 STRING2) tests for two conditions: (1) the length of STRING1 is longer than the length of STRING2. (2) the n tokens in STRING2 exactly match the last n tokens in STRING1. If both of these conditions are met, the function will then remove STRING2 from the end of STRING1 and return the resulting string. Otherwise the function will simply return STRING1. For example, (StringPostremoveFn "I like to bicycle" "to bicycle") returns "I like ". However, (StringPostremoveFn "like to" "I like to bicycle") would return "like to".
label: String Postremove Fn

A variable-arity partial SetDenotingFunction that is a specialization (via genlFunctions) of TheCovering (q.v.), and is used to specify a set of two or more collections or mathematical sets that partition some set or collection (see partitionedInto). For example, the fact that the collection Whale is partitioned into the collections BaleenWhale and ToothedWhale can be expressed as '(partitionedInto Whale (ThePartition BaleenWhale ToothedWhale))'.

If SOC1, ..., SOCn (n>=2) are pairwise-disjoint SetOrCollections, (ThePartition SOC1 ... SOCn) is the set (see Set_Mathematical) whose elements are exactly SOC1, ..., SOCn. If SOC1, ..., SOCn are not all mutually disjoint, then the function returns no value and '(ThePartition SOC1 ... SOCn)' is undefined (q.v.).

Note that ThePartition is simply a restriction of the function TheSet (q.v.) to argument-sequences of length two or greater whose members are pairwise-disjoint (see disjointWith) sets or collections.

An instance of UnaryFunction and CollectionDenotingFunction. (UnitOfMoneyOfGeopoliticalEntityFn GPE) denotes the collection of instances of UnitOfMoney which are part of GPE's monetary system.

For example, Dollar_UnitedStates, Cent_UnitedStates, and MillionDollars are instances of (UnitOfMoneyOfGeopoliticalEntityFn UnitedStatesOfAmerica); Euro is an instance of (UnitOfMoneyOfGeopoliticalEntityFn EuropeanUnion); Dollar_HongKong is an instance of (UnitOfMoneyOfGeopoliticalEntityFn HongKong).

IMPORTANT: When we say that a unit of money UNIT is part of GPE's monetary system, we mean that GPE is the issuer of all currency representing UNIT, i.e. (monetaryUnitIssuedBy UNIT GPE); we do not mean that GPE officially uses UNIT, i.e. (monetaryUnitUsedIn UNIT GPE)--although that is usually the case. Euro is NOT an instance of (UnitOfMoneyTypeByGeopoliticalEntity Italy), even though Italy officially uses the Euro; for it is the EuropeanUnion, not Italy, that issues currency representing the Euro.

Characters have exactly the same hexidecimal code in ASCII as they do in Unicode except the ASCII hex code is two digits and Unicode is four. (The ASCII hex code of the character 'A' is 41 and the Unicode hex code is 0041.) The Unicode Consortium works in conjunction with the InternationalOrganizationForStandardization (ISO/IEC/JTC1) and Unicode is compatible with the International Standard 10646.

label: Cyc's knowledge about transportation
TransportationMt
items.comment: This is a microtheory which should contain a body of axioms and constants relevant to transportation broadly construed. The scope of this mt is broader than most people initially realize since it includes all manner of transportation events (see TransportationEvent) including not only 'typical' transportation events such as train transportation, horseback riding, but also blood cells transporting nutrients, dust particles transporting germs etc.. Basically, any axioms dealing with how one object facilitates the motion of another by moving along with it (see definition of TransportationEvent) are appropriate assertions for this microtheory. Currently (March 97) there are no identifiable domain assumptions, however, it seems intuitively obvious that given their number and complexity that axioms about transportation should be modularized into their own microtheory. Prime exemplars of assertions that should go in here are `transporters and transportees are disjoint' or `passengers are usually in SittingPosture.'. A borderline positive exemplar of an assertion that should go in here is `windsurfing transportees get wet'. This assertion seems not relevant enough to transportation in general, but rather to specific facts about late 20th C recreation. Since such an mt does not currently (March 97) exist, it can go here, although, finding/creating a more specific mt should be given high priority. A negative exemplar assertion would be one that did not mention an instance of TransportationEvent or any specialization of transporter, transportees.

An indexical term that can be used to denote some indeterminate chunk of time that starts after the time of the context. For example, to represent the statement "in the future dogs will talk" we could assert: 
   (ist (MtSpace CURRENT-MONAD (MtTimeDimFn CURRENT-TIME))

The above could be given a minimal interpretation in any microtheory like the following 
(ist (MtSpace CURRENT-MONAD (MtTimeDimFn CURRENT-TIME))
       (thereExists ?FUTURE-INTERVAL
        (and
          (startsAfterEndingOf ?FUTURE-INTERVAL CURRENT-TIME)
          (isa ?FUTURE-INTERVAL TimeInterval)
          (ist (MtSpace CURRENT-MONAD (MtTimeDimFn ?FUTURE-TIME))
            ((TypeCapableFn behaviorCapable) Dog Talking performedBy))))

items.comment: TheVertexList is a function similar to TheList. The salient differences between the two are that TheVertexList (i) returns a list of length at least three, (ii) returns a list of instances of Point, (iii) no three consecutive list members are collinearPoints, neither are the next to last member, last member, and first member collinearPoints, nor are the last member, first member, and second member collinearPoints. These odd restrictions are needed since the result of TheVertexList is intended to correspond to the vertices of an instance of Polygon where the order of the list corresponds to the order of the vertices when the perimeter is traversed in a counter-clockwise direction. The first restriction above is required since polygons have at least three sides, while the last condition reflects the convention that no three consecutive vertices are collinearPoints.

A unary function that takes a CycLPropositionalSentence (q.v.) to the Proposition it expresses with respect to the intended interpretation of the CycL language. (ThatFn SENTENCE) is the proposition that SENTENCE is true. For example, the non-atomic term 
  (ThatFn (likesAsFriend Muffet #$Murray))
denotes the proposition that Muffet like Murray.

Note that the argument-place of ThatFn is "implicitly quoted" (see quotedArgument). Thus the above non-atomic term was constructed by applying the functor ThatFn to the likesAsFriend sentence directly; there was no need to wrap the sentence in Quote. Note further that, because of this quoted argment-place, ThatFn is not related to the predicate expresses (which has no quoted argument-place) via functionCorrespondingPredicate. But for any CycLPropositionalSentence SENTENCE, the following holds: 

  (expresses (Quote SENTENCE) (ThatFn SENTENCE)) .

items.comment: StringPreremoveFn is an evaluatable function that takes two strings as its arguments. (StringPreremoveFn STRING1 STRING2) tests for two conditions: (1) the length of STRING1 is longer than the length of STRING2. (2) the n tokens in STRING2 exactly match the first n tokens in STRING1. If both of these conditions are met, the function will then remove STRING2 from the beginning of STRING1 and return the resulting string. Otherwise the function will simply return STRING1. For example, (StringPreremoveFn "I like to bicycle" "I like") returns " to bicycle". However, (StringPreremoveFn "like to" "I like to bicycle") would return "like to".
label: String Preremove Fn

items.comment: A UnaryFunction and EvaluatableFunction_Contextualized. Evaluating an expression of the form (TextTopicStructureFn TEXT) will return a list of lists of lists of length three. The function presumes that it is receiving a natural language expression containing at least one sentence. The elements of the overall list will represent the individual sentences contained in TEXT. Those elements are ordered based on the sequence of their appearance in TEXT. Each of those 'middle' lists represents a sentence. Its elements represent Cyc's understanding of the words in the sentence. Each element is a list of length 3 and they are ordered relative to the words appearance in the individual sentences. The first element is a CharacterString that represents a particular word in the sentence. The second element is a SpeechPart. The third element is a Set_Mathematical containing the possible denotations of the first element of the list based on the part of speech that is the second element. The possible denotations receive some filtering to remove overly abstract or 'ke irrelevant' concepts.
label: Text Topic Structure Fn
TextTopicStructureFn

items.comment: An instance of IndividualDenotingFunction. TimeIntervalBetweenFn takes two instances of TemporalThing as its arguments and returns an instance of ContinuousTimeInterval (q.v.). (TimeIntervalBetweenFn BEFORE AFTER) is the largest time interval strictly between the TemporalThings BEFORE and AFTER. That is, it denotes the time interval beginning immediately after the end of BEFORE and ending immediately before the start of AFTER. It must be true that AFTER starts after BEFORE ends; i.e. (startsAfterEndingOf AFTER BEFORE). Also, the interval between AFTER and BEFORE should not be empty. Finally, every interval returned by TimeIntervalBetweenFn is temporallyContinuousDuring (q.v.). See also TimeIntervalInclusiveFn, a function that returns a time interval that includes the defining temporal things.

items.comment:
A binary PredicateDenotingFunction that takes an N-ary predicate PRED and an N-length list of collections to a predicate that is a typed-specialization (see typedGenlPreds) of PRED, such that each of its argument-places is restricted (beyond the constraints it inherits from PRED) to instances of the respective collection in the list.

If PRED is an N-ary Predicate and ARG-SIGN-LIST an N-length list of Collections such that no collection in the list is disjoint with (any of) the argIsa -constraint(s) on the corresponding argument-place of PRED, then (TypedSpecPredWithArgSignatureFn PRED ARG-SIGN-LIST) is the N-ary predicate SPEC such that: 

  1. PRED is a typedGenlPreds of SPEC.
  2. Any argIsa or argGenl constraint on PRED also holds of the corresponding argument-place of SPEC.
  3. For each member COLI of ARG-SIGN-LIST, (argIsa SPEC I COLI) holds.
For example, (TypedSpecPredWithArgSignatureFn objectStartingDate (TheList Animal Date)) is the predicate birthDate.

As the example shows, a given COLI might be the same as, or a proper specialization of (see genls), an argIsa constraint on the Ith place of PRED.

Note that the term (TypedSpecPredWithArgSignatureFn PRED ARG-SIGN-LIST) is undefined if either (i) the lengthOfList of ARG-SIGN-LIST differs from the arity of PRED or (ii) any of the COLI in ARG-SIGN-LIST is disjointWith any collection CONSTRAINT such that (argIsa PRED I CONSTRAINT) holds.

See also the corresponding predicate typedGenlPredWithArgumentSignature.
label: Typed Spec Pred With Arg Signature Fn
TypedSpecPredWithArgSignatureFn

An indexical term that can be used to denote some indeterminate chunk of time that ends before the time of the context. For example, to represent the statement "in the future dogs can't talk" we could assert: 
   (ist (MtSpace CURRENT-MONAD (MtTimeDimFn CURRENT-TIME))
    (holdsIn ThePast_Generic(typeBehaviorIncapable Dog Talking performedBy)))
The above could be given a minimal interpretation in any microtheory like the following 
(ist (MtSpace CURRENT-MONAD (MtTimeDimFn CURRENT-TIME))
       (thereExists ?INTERVAL
        (and
          (startsAfterEndingOf CURRENT-TIME ?INTERVAL)
          (isa ?INTERVAL TimeInterval)
          (ist (MtSpace CURRENT-MONAD (MtTimeDimFn ?INTERVAL))
            (typeBehaviorIncapable Dog Talking performedBy))))

TravelInfoForFn takes as argument an individual and returns the collection of all PropositionalInformationThings which include information about travelling to, from, and around the location of the individual, as well as other travel services such as car rental and accommodations in that location. For example, (TravelInfoForFn (OlympicsFn (YearFn 2000))) returns the collection of all information about getting to, from, and around Sydney, Australia, as well as information about lodging and car rental services in Sydney, Australia.
